<PillarLayout
  title="Crisis Navigation — Preparation, Response, and Recovery for Families of Significant Means"
  description="How families of significant means prepare for, respond to, and recover from behavioral health crises, legal jeopardy, medical emergencies, and reputational threats."
  pillar="Crisis Navigation"
  articles={articles}
>
  <p>
    Crisis does not announce itself. A call at 2 a.m. A message from counsel. A headline that should not exist. For families of significant means, the nature of crisis is shaped by factors that most advisory frameworks never address — the intersection of wealth, visibility, behavioral health, and the expectations of discretion that define how these families navigate the world.
  </p>

  <p>
    This section of the Fiduciary Health Guide addresses what the traditional advisory landscape does not: the practical, operational, and human dimensions of crisis in families where the stakes extend beyond the immediate situation to encompass reputation, legacy, multigenerational wealth structures, and the complex professional ecosystems that surround significant family wealth.
  </p>

  <h2>The Gap in Crisis Preparation</h2>

  <p>
    Most families of significant means have estate plans, investment policies, and insurance programs. Few have crisis preparedness frameworks. Fewer still have frameworks that integrate behavioral health considerations, legal contingencies, reputational risk management, and the coordination protocols required when a crisis simultaneously affects clinical care, legal strategy, family governance, and public exposure.
  </p>

  <p>
    This gap is not a reflection of negligence. It reflects the reality that the professional advisory ecosystem is structured in silos. The attorney, the wealth advisor, the family office director, the physician — each operates within a defined scope. When crisis arrives, it respects no such boundaries. The most consequential moments in a family's history often require coordinated action across every one of these domains simultaneously.
  </p>

  <h2>What Crisis Looks Like at This Level</h2>

  <p>
    A behavioral health crisis in a family of significant means is fundamentally different from the same crisis in a family of ordinary means. The clinical dimensions may be similar, but the operational dimensions are not. Privacy requirements are more complex. Media exposure risk is greater. The financial structures surrounding the individual — trusts, business interests, board positions — create cascading implications that must be managed concurrently with clinical care.
  </p>

  <p>
    Legal crises carry similar complexity. When a family member faces criminal charges or civil litigation, the family's professional advisory team must coordinate legal defense, reputation management, trust and estate implications, and family communication — often within hours, not days. The advisor who has thought through these scenarios in advance provides immeasurably more value than the advisor who encounters them for the first time when the call arrives.
  </p>

  <h2>The Fiduciary's Position</h2>

  <p>
    For fiduciaries — trust officers, wealth advisors, family office directors — crisis creates a particular tension. Fiduciary duty demands action in the beneficiary's best interest, but "best interest" during a behavioral health crisis or legal emergency is rarely clear. It requires judgment that balances immediate safety against long-term relationships, clinical recommendations against family dynamics, legal strategy against emotional reality.
  </p>

  <p>
    The articles in this section provide frameworks for exercising that judgment. They address not only what to do in specific crisis scenarios, but how to prepare before crises occur — how to build the relationships, establish the protocols, and develop the institutional knowledge that transforms crisis response from reactive improvisation into coordinated, deliberate action.
  </p>

  <h2>The Content That Does Not Exist Elsewhere</h2>

  <p>
    This is perhaps the most differentiated section of the Fiduciary Health Guide. The intersection of behavioral health, significant wealth, fiduciary responsibility, and crisis management is not addressed comprehensively anywhere in the professional literature. Advisors who encounter these situations often navigate them without precedent, without frameworks, and without the vocabulary to discuss them with colleagues or clients.
  </p>

  <p>
    The articles below are designed to fill that gap. Each addresses a specific category of crisis with the depth, specificity, and discretion that families of significant means and their trusted advisors require. They are written for the professional who will one day receive the call — and for the family that wants to ensure the right people are prepared to answer it.
  </p>
